RABIES - INDONESIA (EAST NUSA TENGGARA), CANINE, HUMAN
*******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Fri 4 Mar 2011
Source: The Jakarta Post, National New [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/03/04/hundreds-e-nusa-tenggara-treated-rabies.html>


Hundreds in E. Nusa Tenggara treated for rabies
-----------------------------------------------
At least 242 residents of Sikka, East Nusa Tenggara, are undergoing
intensive care in health centers after becoming infected with the
rabies virus, local authorities say. The residents were bitten by
rabid animals between January and February [2011], Sikka Health Agency
chief Delly Pasande said Friday [4 Mar 2011], as quoted by
.

"The number of people bitten by rabid dogs is in the hundreds," he
said. Delly said the large number of rabies patients was a result of
insufficient preventive measures on the part of the local Husbandry
Agency. "The problem lies in husbandry. The health [field] is only the
after effect. The most important thing is for preventive measures to
be taken by the husbandry agency," he said.

The region is also lacking rabies vaccines. Currently there are 169
ampules of vaccine, but this could only last the region until
mid-March. The chosen strategy would be selective extermination and
vaccination of rabid dogs. "Vaccines for humans are very expensive,
while the ones for dogs are much cheaper," Delly said.

